  "body": "I'm using the following simple test code:\r\n\r\n```\r\ncontract Test {\r\n    function test_origin() public {\r\n        console.log(\"Test 0\");\r\n        require(tx.origin == 0x56f71EFdBAa5b2d9a285e68ac31F9E524B3eeAB0);\r\n    }\r\n    function test_sender() public {\r\n        console.log(\"Test 0\");\r\n        require(msg.sender == 0x56f71EFdBAa5b2d9a285e68ac31F9E524B3eeAB0);\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nI then run the following command:\r\n\r\n`\r\nforge test --root . --tx-origin 0x56f71EFdBAa5b2d9a285e68ac31F9E524B3eeAB0 --sender 0x56f71EFdBAa5b2d9a285e68ac31F9E524B3eeAB0\r\n`\r\n\r\nBoth tests passes.\r\n\r\nHowever, when I import an EVM by adding `--fork-url` to the command making the line like the following:\r\n\r\n`\r\nforge test --root . --tx-origin 0x56f71EFdBAa5b2d9a285e68ac31F9E524B3eeAB0 --sender 0x56f71EFdBAa5b2d9a285e68ac31F9E524B3eeAB0 --fork-url https://eth-mainnet.alchemyapi.io/v2/<project-key>\r\n`\r\n\r\nThe test_origin one will fail.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, with `--verbosity 3`, two logs will be printed for the second test case. I'm not 100% sure if this has anything to do with the above bug.",
